Looking for an easy and delicious treat to share this holiday season? #ad Let’s make mini no-bake cheesecakes! These are such a fun and simple way to make festive holiday memories with your family this time of year. 

This recipe uses real @kempscows whipping cream, because well #milkmakesitmerrier! And of course, we love that Kemps dairy products come from family farmers right in the community, like us!

Ingredients
Graham Cracker Crust
* 2 cups graham cracker crumbs 
* 1/3 cup packed light or dark brown sugar
* 1/2 cup unsalted butter, melted

Filling
* 1 cup cold @kempscows heavy whipping cream
* two 8-ounce bricks full-fat cream cheese, softened to room temperature
* 1/3 cup granulated sugar
* 2 Tablespoons sour cream
* 1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
* 1/2 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
* optional: your desired toppings 

Instructions
* Line two standard 12-count muffin pans with cupcake liners.
* Prepare the crust: Pour crumbs into a medium bowl and stir in the brown sugar and melted butter until combined. Spoon 1 1/2 Tablespoons of the crust mixture into each muffin liner. Pack it down. 
*OPTIONAL:Bake the crusts for a quick 5 minutes in a 350°F oven. The crusts are a little sturdier this way.
* Make the filling: Using a mixer, whip the heavy cream into stiff peaks,about 3 minutes. Set aside. Using a mixer, beat the cream cheese and granulated sugar together on medium speed until smooth and creamy. Add the sour cream, lemon juice, and vanilla extract. Beat on mediumspeed until smooth and combined, about 1 minute. With a rubber spatula, fold the whipped cream into the cheesecake filling until combined.

* Use a spoon or piping bag to transfer the filling on top of the crusts. Spoon or pipe about 2 Tablespoons of filling over each crust.
* Refrigerate the mini cheesecakes in the pans for at least 3 hours and up to 2 days.
* Keep refrigerated until ready to serve. Serve with optional toppings

Did you know dairy farmers work with a wide variety of dairy specialists and professionals?  Today the milk tester paid us a visit and took a sample of milk from every cow. 

He tests the milk for quality and quantity. Quality of milk is a great indicator of the health of the herd and can provide valuable insights into our operation. 

The quality of milk is especially important for farmers as they are paid on the basis of milk components such as fat and protein.

A few things he will test today:
1. Milk yield per cow
2. Fat content of milk
3. Protein content of milk
4. SCC (somatic cell count) Somatic cell count (SCC) is a measurement of how many white blood cells are present in the milk. White blood cells are the infection fighters in our body and so an elevated white blood cell presence or on a dairy farm, an elevated SCC is a signal that there may be an infection that the cow is fighting. Dairy farmers are paid more money for milk that has a low SCC. 

Just one of the many things farmers do to properly care for their herd, produce quality milk and run a profitable business ❤️

Cheeseburger salads + Cheeseburger quesadillas 🍽️ This a always a go-to when I need to prep dinner ahead of time. I simply make the beef ahead of time and assemble the salads and quesadillas when we get home. 

Ingredients 
1lb of ground beef
1/4 cup Ketchup
2 TBS BBQ sauce
1 teaspoon onion powder
Chopped romain or green leaf lettuce 
Diced tomato
Diced dill pickles
Shredded cheddar 
Tortillas

To make the salad:
Brown ground beef and mix in ketchup, bbq sauce and onion powder. Pile some chopped lettuce on each plate. Pile on a good quantity of the meat mixture, then top with plenty of grated Cheddar. Add diced tomato, chunks of pickles and any other toppings you’d like. Serve immediately. 

To make the quesadillas:
Brown ground beef and mix in ketchup, bbq sauce and onion powder. Grab a tortilla and add to greases skillet. , add to skillet. Top half the tortilla with ½ cup cheese, ¼ of the cooked beef. Top with pickle slices,more cheese and top with a tortilla. Cook until cheese is melted and the tortilla is golden brown on one side, about 2 minutes. 
Flip quesadilla and continue cooking until all the cheese is melted and the second side is golden brown. Slice and serve.

Feed calves with me!

We feed our calves milk at 5 a.m. and 5 p.m.  in addition to milk, all calves receive free choice water and grain. 

Why milk replacer? It’s just what works best for us and our facility right now. One day we hope to feed whole milk (because the cow’s definitely produce enough of it!) Currently our calves aren’t located close the milking parlor and it would be tricky to get the whole milk to the calves. 

Why calf hutches? Young dairy calves very sensitive immune systems and hutches allow us to provide them with shelter, proper ventilation and plenty of individual TLC. Hutches also protect calves from disease and illness the adult herd could be carrying. Calves stay in these hutches for just a few short weeks and then moved to a group pen with outside space. 

What am I using to deliver the milk and water? A milk taxi. It rocks!

Big doesn’t mean bad. 

On our farm, we milk 700 cows and on the farm I grew up on, they milk 1,500 cows.  Due to their size and modern facilities, both would fit into the “factory farm” stereotype. 

However, neither farm is anything like a factory. 

As our families grew, so did our farm.  We needed more cows to support our growing family and to allow all family members to be involved in the business.  By increasing the number of cows, we are able to do what we love and make a decent living. 

A majority of farms put their animals and employees first and take pride in what they do and how they do it. 

Just like you would judge a book by its cover, don’t judge a farm by its size. ❤️

THE MYTH: Dairy farmers pump cows full of antibiotics. 

THE TRUTH: We use antibiotics only when warranted and find them to be a great tool when it comes to a sick animal. 

Antibiotics are expensive and using them willy-nilly is not cost effective. Practicing daily cow comfort and care is much easier.

Do you have to worry about the antibiotics given to a cow invading your dairy products? 

Absolutely not. 

Every load of milk that leaves our dairy is tested for antibiotics before it leaves our farm AND when it reaches the creamery. 

If the load tests positive for antibiotics, the ENTIRE load of milk will be disposed of and the farm will be out a lot of money.  No dairy farmer wants to lose thousands of dollars or produce an unsafe product, so farmers take antibiotics very seriously. 

We use antibiotics when necessary and follow the label’s instructions.  Farmers use antibiotics to help sick animals, while still producing a safe, quality product

One-pot Creamy Chicken and Asparagus Pasta

INGREDIENTS
1 pound Boneless Skinless Chicken Breast
1 teaspoon Oil
1 tablespoon of butter
4 cups Rotini, or any other short pasta shape
2 cups Chicken Broth
2 cups Cold Milk
1 teaspoon Garlic Powder
1 teaspoon of Italian seasoning 
1 pound Asparagus, sliced into 1 inch pieces
1-2 cups of Italian cheese blend
1 tablespoon of lemon juice. 
8 oz of button mushrooms(optional)
Salt and Pepper, to taste

INSTRUCTIONS:
Season the chicken breasts with salt and pepper on both sides. 

To a large skillet, add oil and heat. Brown the chicken on both sides, then reduce the heat to medium and cover the skillet with a lid. Checking from time to time, cook the chicken until it’s done all the way to the center and juices run clear. Remove the chicken from the skillet, cover and set aside. 

(Optional) Add a tablespoon of butter to the skillet and cook mushrooms until tender. Set aside. 

In the same pot, add the pasta, broth, milk, Italian seasoning and garlic powder to the skillet. Season with salt and pepper and stir well. Bring to a boil, then reduce the heat and simmer for 5 minutes (do not cover with a lid). Add the sliced asparagus and finish cooking until the pasta and asparagus are done and the sauce has thickened.
Stir cheese, lemon and mushrooms into the pasta. Slice the chicken breast and serve immediately with the pasta.

Spring is coming. (I think). Soon, your Instagram newsfeed will be flooded with videos and photos of dairy farmers letting their cattle out to pasture. They are fun and beautiful videos to watch; the cows frolicking onto green grass with blue skies in the background. They are happy cows, no doubt.
 
Now here is the deal, my cows don’t go on pasture. In fact, there are many dairy farms that don’t have cows on pasture. Does this mean the cows aren’t happy or that the farmers are “bad”?
 
Absolutely not.

Friends, there is more than one way to raise cattle and there is no right way or wrong way.
 
Some farmers have 70 cows and some farmers have 1,500 cows.

Some farmers milk their cows 2x day and some farmers milk their cows 3x day.

Some farmers use a parlor to milk cows and some farmers use robots.

Some farmers are conventional and some farmers are organic.

Some farmers breed for big, show-type cows and some farmers breed for small cows.
 
The list of differences from farm to farm could go on and on. As long as the cows are properly fed, cared for and have a comfortable place to relax, then they are happy and the farmer is doing his/her job.

Ingredients:
1 pound bacon
1/2 white onion, chopped

INSTRUCTIONS:

Hormones in milk? Should you worry? 

No. 

Hormones are simply chemical messengers — and often proteins — produced naturally in both animal and plant foods– from celery to salmon.  Because of this, there are no “hormone-free” foods, including milk. 

Like other foods, all milk naturally contains very small amounts of hormones, but the body breaks them down during digestion, meaning they become instantly inactive. While there’s no such thing as a “hormone-free” milk (or any “hormone-free” food). 

Some farmers use to use a synthetic hormone to help direct nutrients to the udder  to increase milk production. While it was deemed safe by the FDA and used for several years, it’s no longer in use due to consumer preferences. Most creameries don’t accept milk from farmers that use rBSt. 

No matter what your choice is in the dairy case, know it is safe, nutritious and from farmers who care.

If you ask me, I think cows are pretty darn cool. Cattle have a  four-chambered stomach, which helps them get the nutrients they need from a variety of plants that humans don’t consume or can’t digest. 

Cattle also act  as “upcyclers” in our food system by upgrading human inedible material or edible food waste into high-quality protein and essential micronutrients.

They can take items like brewers’ grains, pea pulp, beet tops, and potato peelings and turn those products into beef or milk. These byproducts, or leftovers, are often mixed into their feed, along with other grasses or hay like alfalfa and grains like corn.

THE MYTH: Dairy farmers pump cows full of antibiotics. 

THE TRUTH: We use antibiotics only when warranted and find them to be a great tool when it comes to a sick animal. 

The other day we discovered a sick cow. Although we do our best to prevent our animals from getting sick, it can still happen. 

This cow had contracted mastitis so we brought her to the hospital pen and administered fluids and antibiotics. 

Do you have to worry about the antibiotics given to a cow invading your dairy products? 

Absolutely not. 

Every load of milk that leaves our dairy is tested for antibiotics before it leaves our farm AND when it reaches the creamery. 

If the load tests positive for antibiotics, the ENTIRE load of milk will be disposed of and the farm will be out a lot of money.  No dairy farmer wants to lose thousands of dollars or produce an unsafe product, so farmers take antibiotics very seriously. 

We use antibiotics when necessary and follow the label’s instructions.  Farmers use antibiotics to help sick animals, while still producing a safe, quality product. 

Thankful we were able to make this cow feel better. Not sure it would have been possible without antibiotics.

Raise you hand if you like one-pot meals? I mean who doesn’t?? You’re gonna love this creamy sun dried tomato beef orzo because it’s quick, easy and only requires one pot. 

It was the perfect meal to whip up after calf chores. Not lying, the kids even ate it! Was it luck? Will they eat it again in thru future? TBD. But it was a win last night and I plan on making it again. 

INGREDIENTS 1 pound lean ground beef 1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes optional 1/2 teaspoon Italian seasoning 1 cup uncooked orzo pasta 1 (14 fluid ounce) can tomato sauce 1 cup beef broth
1 (60z) jar sun dried tomato pesto 1 cup heavy/whipping cream 1/2 cup freshly grated parmesan cheese 2 cups fresh baby spinach Salt & pepper to taste

* Add the ground beef to a soup pot/Dutch oven and break it up a little bit with your spoon. Let it cook, without stirring, over medium-high heat for 5-6 minutes. 
* Stir in the garlic, red pepper flakes, Italian seasoning, and orzo. Cook for about a minute. 
* Stir in the tomato sauce, beef broth, pesto,cream  and seasoning. Once it starts to bubble, cover and continue cooking for 10 minutes, stirring fairly often (so the orzo doesn’t stick to the bottom of the pot). You will likely need to turn the heat down a bit. 
* Take the pot off the heat, stir in the parmesan and spinach, and cover the pot for about 3-5 minutes or until it has thickened up to your liking. Season with salt & pepper as needed and serve immediately.

THE MYTH: Dairy farmers pump cows full of antibiotics.

Do you have to worry about the antibiotics given to a cow invading your dairy products? 

Absolutely not. 

Every load of milk that leaves our dairy is tested for antibiotics before it leaves our farm AND when it reaches the creamery. 

If the load tests positive for antibiotics, the ENTIRE load of milk will be disposed of and the farm will be out a lot of money.  No dairy farmer wants to lose thousands of dollars or produce an unsafe product, so farmers take antibiotics very seriously. 

We use antibiotics when necessary and follow the label’s instructions.  Farmers use antibiotics to help sick animals, while still producing a safe, quality product.

How often do you think about propane? Until recently, my answer to that question was “not often.” Propane heats our home, our milking parlor, and runs the clothes dryers for parlor towels. It is the source of energy for our water heaters that allow us to sanitize equipment, wash buckets and bottles, mix-up milk replacers, warm drinking fountains — the list goes on and on.
 
We initially chose to utilize propane because of its reliability and accessibility; it seemed like a no-brainer. More than 800,000 farms trust propane as a reliable energy source for their operations, so why wouldn’t we? Now we were curious, was there more to know about propane? Was it really the best choice or were we just using it because so many other farm families were?
 
We #partner with @propane_council to learn more about the energy option we rely on day in and day out. We learned just how versatile, efficient, and cost-effective propane is.  It was clear that propane was the smart choice and now I consider myself a bit of a propane guru.

Tonight’s one-pot meal is an adaptation of a family fave because I was missing a few ingredients. 🙈

ONE POT CREAMY BEEF ORZO

INGREDIENTS
1 pound lean ground beef
1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes, optional
1/2 teaspoon Italian seasoning
1 cup uncooked orzo pasta
1 (14 fluid ounce) can tomato sauce
1 cup beef broth
1 (60z) jar sun dried tomato pesto
1 cup heavy/whipping cream
1/2 cup freshly grated parmesan cheese
2 cups fresh baby spinach
Salt & pepper to taste

INSTRUCTIONS:
Add the ground beef to a soup pot/Dutch oven and break it up a little bit with your spoon. Let it cook, without stirring, over medium-high heat for 5-6 minutes.

Stir in the garlic, red pepper flakes, Italian seasoning, and orzo. Cook for about a minute.

Stir in the tomato sauce, beef broth, pesto,cream, orzo and seasoning. Once it starts to bubble, cover and continue cooking for 10 minutes, stirring fairly often (so the orzo doesn’t stick to the bottom of the pot). You will likely need to turn the heat down a bit.

Take the pot off the heat, stir in the parmesan and spinach, and cover the pot for about 3-5 minutes or until it has thickened up to your liking. Season with salt & pepper as needed and serve immediately.

The good news is everyone is safe and warmer temps come back next week. 🙌🏼

It’s been a chilly one in the Midwest! But, rest assured, the animals are doing alright. 

Cows actually have a higher body temperature and a homegrown winter coat that keeps them warm when temps drop. Of course, nobody, not even animals are super happy when temps hit well below zero. 

We protect our animals with shelter, fluffy and dry bedding and a high energy diet.
